1. add the ability to edit current requests, that is items on current requests in restock management the same way we are able to edit items on purchase orders (requests should only be able to be editted if not linked to a PO)

   Fixed implementation:
   - Added a server action, `updateRestockRequest`, that updates restock request line items only when the request has no `purchase_order_id` and is still in an editable request state (`requested` or `on_hold`). It rejects linked requests so developers do not accidentally edit a request that must be changed from its purchase order.
   - The action validates that every submitted line has a product, item name, quantity of at least 1, and non-negative unit cost; rejects submitted item IDs that do not belong to the request; deletes removed lines; updates existing lines; inserts newly added supplier-product lines; recalculates `restock_requests.total_amount`; updates timestamps; and writes a `restock_history` entry.
   - The Current Requests detail modal now shows an "Edit Request Items" button for editable, unlinked requests. The edit modal mirrors purchase-order editing: admins can change item names, quantities, unit costs, remove lines, and add linked supplier products with search and pagination.
   - Linked requests intentionally do not get the current-request edit button. Those requests continue to be edited from the linked PO, which preserves the existing PO/request synchronization path.

   Truthful verification:
   - Run `npx tsc --noEmit` to verify TypeScript accepts the new action types, imports, modal state, and edit submit payloads.
   - Run `npm run lint` to verify the changed React/Next files have no lint warnings or errors.
   - Run `npm run build` to verify the production Next.js build compiles the restock workflow changes and collects page data successfully.
   - Manual database/UI verification: create or find a restock request with `purchase_order_id IS NULL`, open Restock Management > Current Requests > request detail, click "Edit Request Items", edit an existing line, remove a line, add a linked supplier item, and save. Confirm `restock_items` reflects the exact changed/deleted/inserted rows, `restock_requests.total_amount` equals the sum of active edited lines, and `restock_history.action = 'items_updated'` was inserted.
   - Manual guard verification: link a request to a PO, return to Current Requests/request detail, and confirm there is no "Edit Request Items" button. Also call `updateRestockRequest` against that linked request and confirm it returns the linked-request error instead of modifying rows.

2. in restock management, make the unscheduled purchase order button hide on mobile, that is in mobile view and in desktop portrait view

   Fixed implementation:
   - The "Unscheduled Purchase Order" button is now hidden below the `xl` breakpoint and only rendered as an inline-flex control on extra-wide layouts. This removes it from mobile/tablet and typical desktop-portrait widths while keeping it available on wider desktop layouts.

   Truthful verification:
   - Run `npx tsc --noEmit`, `npm run lint`, and `npm run build`.
   - Manual responsive verification: inspect Restock Management at widths below 1280px and confirm the "Unscheduled Purchase Order" button is absent; inspect at 1280px or wider and confirm the button is visible.

3. in the restock management tabs, the search feature, it works, but I want it to also use a dropdown to show the requests that match results, when restock requests(not supplier lookup) match search terms (there is a difference between showing the requests themselves that match the results and the supplier they are under)

   Fixed implementation:
   - The tab search dropdown for Current Requests and Request History now searches direct request-level data plus item-level data (`product_name`, `product_type`, `notes`, and `product_id`) instead of using supplier/group lookup for the request dropdown.
   - Dropdown matches now list the actual matching restock request rows, with a secondary line showing the matching item and quantity when the search term matched a request item. This distinguishes direct request matches from the grouped supplier cards underneath.
   - The dropdown respects the active Current Requests and Request History filters, so it does not show requests excluded by the currently selected status filter.

   Truthful verification:
   - Run `npx tsc --noEmit`, `npm run lint`, and `npm run build`.
   - Manual UI verification: search for a product name or item note that exists inside a restock request but does not match the supplier name. Confirm the dropdown opens and shows the request number with the matching item summary. Click the dropdown row and confirm it opens that exact request detail, not just the supplier group.
   - Manual filter verification: apply "Requested only", "Linked to PO only", or a history status filter, repeat the search, and confirm the dropdown only shows requests allowed by that active filter.
